{
  "query": "What are the typical outcomes when primates are reintroduced into habitats where the same species is already present?",
  "relevant_summary": "When primates are reintroduced into habitats where the same species is already present, survival outcomes vary significantly across species and time periods. Four before-and-after studies in Guinea and the Republic of Congo found that the majority of reintroduced chimpanzees survived for at least one to five years after reintroduction (Action 1591). However, one study in Uganda found that a reintroduced chimpanzee repeatedly returned to human settlements, while a study in Senegal found that a reintroduced chimpanzee was reunited with its mother (Action 1591).\n\nFor orangutans, one study in Malaysia found that a majority survived reintroduction, but a controlled study in Malaysia found that a reintroduced population had declined 33 years after reintroduction (Action 1591). Population outcomes also varied: one study in Belize found that primate population increased five years after reintroduction, while one study in Thailand found that primate population declined post-reintroduction (Action 1591).\n\nSurvival rates showed mixed patterns. Six studies in Brazil, French Guiana, Indonesia, Madagascar, and South Africa found that a minority of primates survived for at least fifteen weeks to seven years after reintroduction, while five studies in Brazil, French Guiana, Gabon, and South Africa found that a majority of primates survived for at least two months to one year (Action 1591).\n\nBehavioral integration appeared successful in some cases. Two controlled studies in Madagascar and Indonesia found that reintroduced primates had similar diets to individuals in wild populations, and one controlled study in Indonesia found that reintroduced primates showed similar behaviour to wild individuals. One study in Brazil found that a reintroduced muriqui rejoined a wild group after reintroduction (Action 1591).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1591"
  ]
}

