{
  "query": "For what length of time have translocated primate populations been observed to survive post-release?",
  "relevant_summary": "Translocated primate populations have been observed to survive for varying lengths of time post-release, ranging from months to decades. Short-term survival studies show that majority of primates survived for 5-30 months following translocation from development sites to natural habitat (action 1558), while one study found that a minority survived for at least 18 months (action 1558). Medium-term observations include studies showing most reintroduced chimpanzees survived over 1-5 years (action 1553), most reintroduced or translocated primates survived at least four months (action 1553), and majority of chimpanzees survived for at least two to five years after reintroduction (action 1567). Long-term survival data includes primate populations that persisted 4-55 years after reintroduction (action 1567), a population of chimpanzees that increased 25 years after reintroduction (action 1567), one study that found a reintroduced population of orangutans had declined 33 years after reintroduction (action 1591), and a population of translocated olive baboons that were still surviving 16 years after translocation (action 1553). However, some studies also found high mortality rates, with most reintroduced golden lion tamarins not surviving over seven years (action 1553) and 90% of reintroduced M\u00fcller's Bornean gibbons not surviving (action 1553).",
