{
  "query": "What are the effects of installing different types of bridges to mitigate road impacts on arboreal and terrestrial primates?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, different types of bridge installations show varying effects for mitigating road impacts on primates:\n\n**Rope or Pole (Canopy) Bridges:** One study in Brazil found that black lion tamarins and capuchins used a pole bridge to cross a road (Action 1457). A before-and-after study in Belize found that a black howler monkey population increased after the construction of pole bridges over man-made gaps (Action 1457). In Madagascar, a before-and-after study found that all six monitored lemur species used bridges to cross roads and pipelines (Action 1457).\n\n**Rope Bridges Between Canopies:** Nine studies found that rope bridges were used by a range of mammals, with seven studies finding between three and 25 species using rope bridges (Action 2556). One study found that crossing rates were higher over the canopy bridges than at ground level (Action 2556). A study in Australia found that arboreal marsupials using rope bridges did not suffer high predation rates when doing so (Action 2556).\n\n**Green Bridges (Overpasses):** No evidence was found for the effects of installing green bridges on primate populations specifically (Action 1456).\n\n**Underground Crossings for Terrestrial Species:** While not specifically tested on primates, twenty-five studies found that tunnels, culverts or underpasses under roads were used by various mammals, with seventeen of 20 studies finding that these crossing structures beneath roads were used by mammals (Action 2514). A review found that most studies recorded no evidence of predation of mammals using crossings under roads (Action 2514).",
