tools_called.args:
{"summary": "Permanent human presence at conservation sites shows mixed but generally positive effects on primate conservation success. Continuous monitoring by researchers and veterinarians has shown significant positive outcomes: mountain gorilla populations increased by 168% over 41 years with continuous monitoring by vets alongside other interventions (Action 1554), and mountain gorilla numbers increased over 5-41 years while being continuously monitored by researchers alongside other interventions, with no gorillas killed over one year during continuous monitoring (Action 1511). Black howler monkey numbers increased by 138% over 13 years with permanent monitoring by researchers (Action 1511) and permanent presence of reserve staff (Action 1517). 

Regular anti-poaching patrols demonstrated effectiveness: gorilla populations increased in Rwanda with regular anti-poaching patrols alongside other interventions, no gorillas were killed over 21 months when the number of guards increased, and illegal primate hunting activities reduced in Ghana (Action 1471). Training for anti-poaching rangers showed positive results with no gorillas killed over 21 months after guards received training, increased numbers of immature gorillas in Rwanda, and no primate poaching incidents over three years after ranger training in Cameroon (Action 1477).

However, some studies showed mixed results: numbers of Tana River red colobus and crested mangabeys decreased despite permanent presence of reserve staff (Action 1517), and a reintroduced lar gibbon population declined over three years despite permanent staff presence (Action 1517). Monitoring surveillance strategies and law enforcement showed positive outcomes with more gorillas and chimpanzees observed after implementation (Action 1481).", "action_ids": ["1554","1511","1517","1471","1477","1481"], "query": "How does a permanent human presence at a site influence the success of primate conservation efforts?"}

